exercises.problem:
Consider a sequence of $n$ independent and identically distributed random variables $X_1, X_2, \ldots, X_n$ where each $X_k$ has the following probability distribution:

$$\begin{aligned}
X_k = \begin{cases}
1 & \text{with probability } \frac{1}{2} \\
2 & \text{with probability } \frac{1}{3} \\
-1 & \text{with probability } \frac{1}{6}
\end{cases}
\end{aligned}$$

Define the sample mean as $\bar{X}_n = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{k=1}^n X_k$.

1. Compute the expected value $E(\bar{X}_n)$ and the variance $\operatorname{Var}(\bar{X}_n)$ of the sample mean.
2. Using Chebyshev’s Inequality, find the smallest value of $n$ such that the probability $\mathbb{P}\left(\left|\bar{X}_n - E(\bar{X}_n)\right| \geq 0.1\right) \leq 0.05$.
3. Compare the result obtained in part (2) with the case where each $X_k$ is a Bernoulli random variable with $p = \frac{1}{2}$ (i.e., $X_k = 1$ with probability $\frac{1}{2}$ and $X_k = 0$ with probability $\frac{1}{2}$). Discuss the difference in required sample sizes and explain why this occurs.
